    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Dangerous Cheerleading</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Emma Shanahan letter holds that like every dangerous sport, cheerleading needs enforced safety regulations (March 31 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Cheerleaders Soar Higher, So Do the Risks,'' (front page, March 31):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Cheerleaders Soar Higher, So Do the Risks,'' (front page, March 31):</p>
        <p>I wasn't surprised to read about Jessica Smith's breaking her neck. There isn't a squad at my school, but even if there were one, I wouldn't join.</p>
        <p>One reason is that when people think of cheerleaders, they think miniskirts, blonde hair and jock boyfriends -- and I'm not that kind of girl. The other reason is that it is dangerous.</p>
        <p>Like every dangerous sport, cheerleading needs enforced safety regulations. Cheerleading has you flying through the air -- and gravity doesn't stop for a cheer.</p>
        <p>Judges and coaches are putting too much pressure on girls. An 18-year-old girl doesn't deserve to have her life on the line just to impress peers. Get well soon, Jessica.</p>
        <p>Emma Shanahan  New York, March 31, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
